******
[2]
Date: Wed 19 Jan 2011
Source: Fax sent by Directorate D - Animal Health and Welfare, EU
Health & Consumers DG, Brussels, to CVOs [chief veterinary officers]
of all member countries and Iceland, Switzerland, and Norway [edited]


FMD Bulgaria fax no 13
----------------------
Bulgarian authorities have informed that on 18 Jan 2011, 157
susceptible animals were culled (85 cattle, 69 sheep and lambs, and 3
goats) in the Rezovo village. At the time of the culling, aphthae, and
lesions 2 to 10 days old were observed in the mouths of cattle.

Moreover, today [19 Jan 2011], 21 Turkish buffaloes, which penetrated
illegally the territory of Rezovo village, will also be culled and
disposed of. All animal carcasses were buried in a trench in the land
around the village of Rezovo. Disinfection of all premises where
animals have been kept and roads in the village was performed.

Clinical examination of all cattle in other settlements of Burgas
region so far has not revealed any further cases of clinical signs of
FMD.

--
